1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:02,500
Copilot actually changed my PR into an advertisement.

2
00:00:02,500 --> 00:00:05,000
This is a real complaint that hit the top of Hacker News.

3
00:00:05,000 --> 00:00:08,000
A developer only asked Copilot to fix a spelling error in his PR.

4
00:00:08,000 --> 00:00:10,500
But after the fix, the code was fine, yet the PR footer had an extra line.

5
00:00:10,500 --> 00:00:13,000
It read "Third-party product advertisement" with a link attached.

6
00:00:13,000 --> 00:00:15,500
Even more bizarrely, the product was a "official partner" of Copilot.

7
00:00:15,500 --> 00:00:18,000
So far, it was just absurd, but something even more explosive followed.

8
00:00:18,000 --> 00:00:20,500
Someone searched for the exact ad copy and found nearly identical content.

9
00:00:20,500 --> 00:00:23,000
It had already appeared in over 11,000 GitHub PRs.

10
00:00:23,000 --> 00:00:25,500
The combined commits involved over 1.5 million PRs.

11
00:00:25,500 --> 00:00:28,000
Not only GitHub, but also GitLab PRs were not spared.

12
00:00:28,000 --> 00:00:30,500
Public opinion exploded. The poster said bluntly:

13
00:00:30,500 --> 00:00:33,000
"I knew this kind of mess would happen sooner or later, but I didn't expect it so soon."

14
00:00:33,000 --> 00:00:35,500
Some joked: "Forcing ads in is Microsoft's old habit."

15
00:00:35,500 --> 00:00:38,000
They've been testing user limits since the Windows era.

16
00:00:38,000 --> 00:00:40,500
Some media worried: if PR content with ads is used to train Copilot,

17
00:00:40,500 --> 00:00:43,000
won't AI start pushing ads more and more frequently?

18
00:00:43,000 --> 00:00:45,500
In the face of public backlash, the official response was firm.

19
00:00:45,500 --> 00:00:48,000
They insisted GitHub will never place ads on its platform.

20
00:00:48,000 --> 00:00:50,500
It was all a misunderstanding — Copilot only generated content with product prompts.

21
00:00:50,500 --> 00:00:53,000
The system mistakenly inserted a recommendation prompt into the PR.

22
00:00:53,000 --> 00:00:55,500
It looked like an ad, but it was essentially a product operation error.

23
00:00:55,500 --> 00:00:58,000
It sounds reasonable, but it's hard to fully reassure people.

24
00:00:58,000 --> 00:01:00,500
Because if you look deeper, the logic behind this incident is very realistic.

25
00:01:00,500 --> 00:01:03,000
Both Copilot and the entire AI industry are facing the same problem: where does the money come from?

26
00:01:03,000 --> 00:01:05,500
When the freemium model hits its ceiling, advertising monetization is almost unavoidable.

27
00:01:05,500 --> 00:01:08,000
But this time, it doesn't appear in web sidebars or pop-ups.

28
00:01:08,000 --> 00:01:10,500
Instead, it's directly embedded into the most trusted generated content.

29
00:01:10,500 --> 00:01:13,000
That's why people reacted so strongly.

30
00:01:13,000 --> 00:01:15,500
When AI starts inserting ads into answers, can you still trust it unconditionally?
